<TEXT>
the lameduck sandinista front is 
searching hard for a new identity to help it become a viable 
opposition party by the next presidential election six years from 
now 
so far the partys transformation has included shifting away 
from leftist revolutionary rhetoric and becoming more open and 
mainstream 
sandinismo has a big problem it doesnt know what it is 
said emilio alvarez montalvan a veteran of nicaraguan politics and 
foreign affairs adviser to conservative presidentelect violeta 
barrios de chamorro who is to take office wednesday 
theyre not guerrillas any more theyre not 
marxistleninists they dont like being socialdemocrats by 
definition theyre not socialchristians much less conservatives 
or liberals what are they then they themselves dont know 
alvarez said in a recent interview 
losing the feb 25 general elections to mrs chamorros 14party 
national opposition union was a shock and an embarrassment to the 
sandinistas who had ruled for nearly 11 years 
more than a halfdozen opinion polls had given them a wide lead 
over uno their last campaign rally was the largest political 
gathering in nicaraguan history drawing more than 300000 people 
they lied to us one party leader from the interior ministry 
said bitterly after the final tally showed uno obtained 55 percent 
of the vote 
still the sandinista front got 408 percent of the vote which 
because uno is a coalition still leaves it as the single largest 
party in nicaragua 
that to its leaders means the mass support is still there but 
the partys approach and even its image must change before the next 
elections in six years 
i think the cycle of antiimperialist revolutions is coming to 
an end said victor tirado lopez one of nine commanders of the 
1979 revolution that make up the sandinista fronts national 
directorate therefore we must reexamine our path 
what does the electoral defeat of sandinismo express that the 
people want peace and we cant keep pointing to war to resolve 
social contradictions tirado said in an interview published in 
march in barricada the official sandinista front newspaper 
in 1984 the sandinista front and president daniel ortega 
obtained 64 percent of the vote the war with the usbacked 
contra rebels was about two years old then and the revolutionary 
fervor that had toppled rightist president anastasio somoza was 
still high 
but after a decade of war and economic hardship resulting from a 
us economic embargo and sandinista administrative imcompetence 
nicaraguans apparently decided to believe unos promise that only 
it could bring peace and prosperity to the nation 
the sandinista leadership met in emergency session and came out 
with a pronouncement that gave a glimpse of the partys new 
direction 
we have the total willingness to back all those actions that 
go in favor of the people but we have the willingess and firm will 
to oppose and resist with the strength of the people all those 
actions that go against the people ortega said in a speech less 
than 48 hours after the election 
his vow to rule from below has become the new sandinista 
slogan one that draws strength from a grassroots organization 
built on labor unions farm cooperatives women and youth groups 
after the elections the sandinista front announced it would 
join the socialist international a worldwide association of 
parties that generally advocate socialism through democratic reform 
rather than armed revolution 
that indicates a change of attitude reinforced by last years 
dramatic fall of hardline communist leaders in the soviet bloc 
ten or 20 years ago many people underestimated electoral 
democracy they only accepted armed struggle and insurrection to 
grab power from the bourgueoisie tirado said today times 
have changed 
more recently the sandinistas have rushed to get a hold on mass 
media knowing they will need a public forum 
nearly the entire staff of the voice of nicaragua the 
government radio station has started to move to radio ya a new 
station being set up at sandinista headquarters 
workers at another sandinistadominated radio station la 
primerisima have been given ownership of the facility 
the front also started an alternative nightly news hour called 
extravision broadcast on nicaraguas sole tv station the 
sandinista television system 
the sandinistas already have begun acting like an opposition 
party threatening strikes if the contras dont fulfill an accord 
to dismantle by june 10 
ortega in a televised speech last week said enforcing that 
accord was the sandinistas main objective for the next few months 
it amounted to a description of his job as a political leader and 
gave the party a rallying theme 
