<TEXT>
when nicaraguan president daniel ortega steps 
down on wednesday he will join a rapidly growing but still 
exclusive club 
over the past year and a half wrathful voters in about a dozen 
latin american countries have rebelled against their declining 
living standards by voting incumbent parties out of office in 
nicaragua voters repudiated the revolutionary left elsewhere 
more moderate parties were turned out of power 
in some ways the throw the bums out mentality in latin 
america parallels what occurred last year in eastern europe 
in both regions the trend generally has been toward reducing 
the state role in the economy and adoption of free market 
principles 
but the political upheaval in latin america has been far less 
dramatic than in the east bloc it has taken place not on the 
streets but in the quiet of the voting booth 
ortegas defeat by violeta chamorro on feb 25 was just the 
latest example of central american voters opting for the more 
conservative alternative the pattern has been similar in elections 
in el salvador honduras and costa rica over the past year 
in south america similar examples can be cited in brazil and 
uruguay in the recent election in peru the large majority of the 
votes went to either centrist or rightist candidates leaving the 
nominee of the ruling centerleft party trailing badly 
in chile despite high economic growth rates voters turned 
against 15 years of military rule in 1988 the countrys newly 
elected leadership has promised not to tamper significantly with 
the conservative economic policies of the previous government 
in venezuela argentina ecuador and jamaica the presidents 
were elected as populists but are pursuing economic policies that 
are far more conservative than what they promised during the 
campaign 
in mexico the partido revolucionario institucional is still in 
charge but not without receiving a scare from the voters two years 
ago 
president carlos salinas de gortari is winning praise from 
washington for his efforts to revitalize the mexican economy 
through marketoriented approaches 
throughout the hemisphere there is a recognition that the 
traditional way of doing things hasnt worked 
eva loser an analyst at the center for strategic and 
international studies says there is a widespread tendency to 
throw out what theyve been doing and try something new 
secretary of state james a baker iii has hailed the restoration 
of democracy in the hemisphere but says that breakthrough will be 
meaningless unless it leads to improved living standards 
economists look on the 1980s in latin america as the lost 
decade a time when production investment and consumption all 
dropped the number of latin americans in absolute poverty is 
believed to be far above 100 million 
in 1988 combined inflation in latin america was 420 percent 
when peruvians went to the polls several weeks ago prices were 
soaring at an annual rate of almost 3000 percent 
some countries have had to earmark up to half their export 
earnings for foreign debt payments the declining economies in many 
countries were the result of rockbottom prices for export 
commodities 
that is a problem local governments cannot influence but other 
maladies are homegrown 
douglas payne director of hemispheric affairs for freedom 
house a prodemocracy group based in new york said economic 
stagnation in the hemisphere is partly the result of monopoly 
regulation and protectionism 
more recently he said these problems have been compounded by 
interventionist development policies that created huge 
moneyguzzling state corporations and corrupt nowork 
bureaucracies 
one of the more interesting contests shaping up in the short 
term is expected within the next year in guyana 
there the moderate ruling party will be squaring off against a 
party led by an oldline marxist cheddi jagan who for now is 
the favorite to win 
