<TEXT>
the nonstop rise in college tuition coupled 
with the prospect of major cuts in americas troop strength is 
prompting calls for expanded benefits under veterans educational 
program known as the montgomery gi bill 
the congressional committees that deal with veteran affairs 
recently recommended that veterans secretary edward j derwinski 
propose raising the maximum monthly gi bill benefit 
the pentagon and armed services groups are looking at how the 
program can help ease the impact of demobilization on service 
members who had planned on a military career 
since 1985 the monthly benefit for veterans who pursue fulltime 
study has stood at 300 for a maximum 36 months tuition at public 
institutions has risen 6 percent to 7 percent annually since then 
and is expected to keep rising the pentagon says 
tuition for all highereducation institutions including 
twoyear colleges cost 6800 in 1988 the department of education 
says 
if the program were indexed the benefit would be 464 monthly 
says richard l johnson of the non commissioned officers 
association his figure is based on a pentagon test program 
rep gv sonny montgomery chairman of the house veterans 
affairs committee asked the va in a letter march 26 to raise the 
monthly benefit under his namesake bill to 400 in fiscal 1992 the 
senate va committee gave no dollar figure in its budget 
recommendation 
johnson says the benefits are becoming more critical because of 
pentagon plans to cut military strength the army where gi bill 
enrollment is the highest would drop from 764000 to 580000 
members by 1997 under the latest pentagon plan 
the big concern i have is when we look back through 1970 to 
1975 we had a gi bill that could reasonably support an individual 
who had a wife and child said johnson that would be impossible 
now he said 
under the gi bill then in place the last wartime and draftera 
bill the benefit for a veteran with no dependents rose from 130 a 
month in 1967 to 342 in january 1981 veterans with dependents 
received more 
usage for any gi bill since the program began after world war ii 
peaked in 1976 when 28 million people received training most in 
college 
johnsons concern has also been expressed in the pentagon where 
lt col otis elam says weve been looking at that very hard 
his concern is with the longerterm service member 
when they get out they may not have a job opportunity and may 
need benefits for school said elam associate director for 
education and officer procurement policy in the defense department 
paradoxically a program that was tailored to attract 
highquality recruits and keep them in the service will have to be 
used to ease people out and no one has any idea what impact 
demobilization will have on the present budget projections for the 
program 
the reagan administration had tried to end the program in its 
1987 budget proposal substituting an earlier less popular 
peacetime version the administration said at the time the bill had 
achieved its purpose 
the montgomery gi bill took form amid a debate over how to 
restore the strength and quality of the armed services because of 
that concern the program has incentives for staying in the 
activeduty military or reserves 
under the montgomery bill service members are automatically 
enrolled unless they elect to opt out within two weeks after 
entering the service participants have 100 a month deducted from 
their pay for the first 12 months of service which they do not get 
back if they do not go to school after leaving the service 
as a result of these deductions the pentagon has saved 1 
billion in payroll costs since july 1985 the benefits the bulk of 
which come out of the va budget are only now beginning to be paid 
in large numbers 
the va has predicted that usage of the 300 monthly benefit will 
peak in 1995 and that from then to the turn of the century nearly 
250000 participants will collect about 500 million dollars each 
year or about 1900 each 
