he loved the campus 
despite his anger while held 1182 days by the proiranian 
shiite moslem militants polhill said he tried not to think about 
when he would be released 
freedom is something that believe it or not neither me nor 
my two associates spent a lot of time thinking about he said in 
the syrian interview its a bit like you wish you had a tbone 
steak in front of you 
knowing you were not going to get it right away makes you more 
hungry makes you want that steak more so we didnt spend time 
thinking or talking about when wed be freed 
polhill said he was not mistreated and that his guards tried to 
provide amenities within the limitations placed on them but the 
uncertainties terrified him and his two fellow captives 
we were very much in the dark about our status he said 
we didnt know where we stood that was the worst we didnt know 
when or whether we were ever going to be released 
polhill a diabetic attended cornell university and graduated 
from new york university in 1961 
he later began work as a new york city accountant he was 
described as a photography buff an avid new york giants fan and a 
committed educator 
