<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to consider 
reinstating a hawaii womans assault conviction thrown out because 
a federal magistrate not a federal judge presided over jury 
selection in her trial 
the justices said they will review a ruling that overturned 
darlina frances conviction and fiveyear prison sentence for 
shooting her husband 
mrs france was convicted of assault with a deadly weapon 
assault with intent to murder and related charges she was 
sentenced to five years in prison plus three years probation 
the case was tried in federal court because mrs france and her 
husband neil were living on an army base in hawaii when the 
shooting occurred dec 20 1986 
prosecutors said mrs france shot her husband in the shoulder 
after he took her beer from the refrigerator and put it in the 
backyard they said the couple had argued earlier in the day and 
that she became upset when he knocked over a christmas tree 
mrs france said her husband provoked the shooting by attacking 
her france testified that he believed the gun went off 
accidentally urged that his wife not be prosecuted and said they 
were reconciling 
in overturning mrs frances conviction last september the 9th 
us circuit court relied upon a supreme court ruling the previous 
june 
in it the high court said federal judges to ensure an 
impartial trial may not delegate the task of presiding over jury 
selection to magistrates federal judges unlike magistrates are 
appointed for life to assure they will not be swayed improperly by 
popular opinion 
in the case decided last june the defendants had objected to 
having a magistrate preside over jury selection 
mrs france made no such objection prior to her trial but the 
9th circuit court said the distinction has little significance 
the appeals court said she should not be penalized for failing 
to object to what at the time of her trial was the generally 
accepted rule that magistrates could select juries 
the appeals court in an unusual move also said federal 
prosecutors were too harsh in charging mrs france under a 1984 
federal law that carries a mandatory fiveyear prison term for 
offenders 
we have been left with the sense that darlina france may 
not be the sort of hardened violent offender whom congress had in 
mind when it enacted the 1984 law the appeals court said 
justice department lawyers in the appeal acted on today said 
mrs france forfeited her right to have jury selection conducted by 
a federal judge because she failed to object to the magistrates 
role before trial 
dozens of convictions could be thrown out if the 9th circuit 
court ruling is not reversed the government lawyers said the 9th 
circuit court has jurisdiction in hawaii alaska arizona 
california nevada oregon idaho montana and washington state 
the case is us vs france 891363 
