<TEXT>
the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether prison inmates who testify in federal court proceedings 
should be paid witness fees 
the court said it will hear an appeal by a colorado state prison 
inmate seeking compensation for testifying at a 1988 federal trial 
the inmate richard s demarest testified for the defendant on 
march 15 1988 he said he should be entitled to the same fee as 
anyone else who is a witness in federal court 
the 10th us circuit court of appeals ruled last september that 
federal law does not require that prisoners be paid for appearing 
at federal trials 
beyond their loss of the very modest compensation they might 
receive from participating in prison jobs programs prisoners 
generally do not incur financial costs serving as witnesses the 
appeals court said 
the appeals courted noted that the 30aday witness fee is much 
more that inmates make working in prison industries 
demarest for example is paid 40 a month in his job at the 
arkansas valley correctional facility in crowley colorado 
the appeals court said paying prisoners could lead to abuses 
since it would tempt inmates who number in the millions to file 
suits and then subpoena inmate friends to testify 
the bush administration urged the supreme court to reject 
demarests appeal 
the case is demarest vs manspeaker 895916 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

