<TEXT>
chinese premier li peng arrived today for the 
first visit in 26 years by a chinese head of government to the 
soviet union chinas longtime rival for leadership of the 
communist world 
the fourday trip is to promote normal relations and ease border 
tensions at a time when both countries are confronted with serious 
domestic problems 
the 61yearold premier was expected to hold at least two rounds 
of talks with president mikhail s gorbachev who last may went to 
china in the first visit by a soviet leader in three decades 
lis visit to the ussr underscores the importance of 
continuing the sinosoviet dialogue at the summit level which 
began a year ago and signalled the normalization of relations 
the tass news agency said 
li was met at the airport by premier nikolai ryzhkov and foreign 
minister eduard shevardnadze 
i will be exchanging views with president gorbachev chairman 
ryzhkov and other comrades from the soviet leadership on matters 
concerning bilateral relations and on major international issues of 
common concern li said at the airport 
tass said ryzhkov and peng began meeting monday but did not 
report what they were discussing 
gorbachevs historic visit to china was overshadowed by 
studentled prodemocracy demonstrations in beijing which ended 
weeks later when li and other chinese leaders sent in troops to 
crush the movement 
in moscow gorbachev is contending with the crisis in lithuania 
which declared independence march 11 
the official chinse press before lis departure said his trip 
would have profound significance on peace in asia and the world 
china and the soviet union split over ideological differences in 
1960 and fought a brief border war in 1969 in 1972 china restored 
relations with the united states in part because thenleader mao 
tsetung saw the soviet union as chinas most serious military 
threat 
western diplomats in beijing said china has stressed it will 
never be a docile soviet ally as it was in the 1950s and they 
noted that chinas inherent suspicions of soviet aims have grown 
with gorbachevs reform policies 
the ideological hardliners who now rule china reportedly blame 
gorbachev for the fall of communist parties in eastern europe and 
see perestroika gorbachevs program of political and economic 
reform as leading to the demise of socialism 
tass said both the soviet union and china agreed that the latest 
rounds of talks will not presage a return to the relationship of 
the 1950s but the departure from the confrontation that existed 
in the past 
the news agency said the two sides have shown readiness to 
reduce troops deployed in the area of the sovietchinese border and 
have agreed to a treaty on the reductions 
it said the current talks will enable the two countries to 
improve cooperation in trade economic scientifictechnical 
cultural and other areas 
