<TEXT>
the supreme court today raised the possibility 
that minnesota officials may enforce a traffic safety law against 
certain members of an amish sect in rural fillmore county 
the court set aside a minnesota supreme court ruling that barred 
such enforcement 
the justices told the state court to reconsider the case in 
light of their decision last week allowing states to outlaw the 
religious use of the illegal drug peyote 
in a brief order today issued over two dissenting votes the 
court said the minnesota court should restudy the amish controversy 
after examining the peyote ruling from oregon 
in that case members of the native american church contended 
that punishing the religious use of peyote violated religious 
freedom 
in the minnesota case the state supreme court ruled that 
requiring the amish to display a slowmoving vehicle warning 
emblem on the back of their horsedrawn buggies violated their 
religious freedom 
a state law requires that slowmoving vehicles display a 
yelloworange triangular emblem to warn other drivers the law 
provided for one alternative a black and white triangular emblem 
not all members of the amish sect living in fillmore county in 
southeastern minnesota near the iowa border object to the emblem 
but 14 who did were issued citations for refusing to attach the 
emblems to their black buggies 
the 14 say the loud colors and worldly symbols conflict with 
biblical admonitions against putting their faith in anything but 
god 
a state trial judge ruled that enforcing the traffic law against 
the 14 amish members did not violate any right but the minnesota 
supreme court unanimously threw out all charges against them last 
august 
the states highest court ruled that the requirement infringed 
on the exercise of a sincerely held religious belief and most 
importantly the states compelling interest in traffic safety 
could be served by a lessrestrictive requirement 
noting that the amish do not object to outlining their buggies 
with silver reflective tape or to displaying red lit lanterns to 
supplement the tape the state supreme court said there does 
exist a less restrictive alternative to serve the states public 
safety concerns 
in the appeal acted on today county attorney robert r benson 
argued that the state court impermissibly advances religion by 
allowing the amish special rights which individuals outside that 
religious group cannot enjoy 
lawyers for the amish said benson is wrong 
there is ample room for legislatures and courts to craft 
religious accommodations and yet not establish or advance 
religion they said the minnesota supreme court has not 
established religion by allowing the amish to use reflective tape 
and the traditional red lantern on their buggies instead of forcing 
them to use an orange fluorescent or black worldly symbol 
justices john paul stevens and sandra day oconnor dissented 
from the high courts action today without stating their reasons 
the case is minnesota vs hershberger 89804 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

