<TEXT>
federal safety investigators concluded monday 
that an improperly latched cargo door popped open before a cargo 
plane crashed in texas last year but said they could not determine 
the cause of the crash 
the accident at carswell air force base near fort worth killed 
the pilot and copilot who were the only people aboard the dc9 
operated by evergreen international airlines 
the national transportation safety board after a meeting on the 
march 18 1989 crash said inadequate procedures used by evergreen 
for preflight verification of cargo door security contributed to 
the crash 
the board also blamed the federal aviation administration for 
approving procedures used for verification of cargo door security 
and for failing to order modifications to the open door warning 
system on dc9s used as cargo planes 
mcdonnell douglas was cited for failing to provide the flight 
crew guidance on inflight opening of the cargo door despite 23 
previous incidents involving dc9s and dc8s none of the previous 
incidents resulted in an accident 
the board said klm which owned the aircraft before evergreen 
accomplished only three of the 11 items the manufacturer 
recommended for the main cargo door and evergreen took no 
additional action on the items 
all faaordered actions were taken however investigators said 
the board said the flights copilot probably failed to complete 
the door locking cycle and the captain was not aware of it because 
of the malfunctioning warning system the door opened upon takeoff 
investigators concluded 
the opening of a cargo door could disturb the stability of an 
airliner affecting airspeed and altitude the board said in 
recommending that mcdonnell douglas amend its operating manual to 
include information about the effects of an open cargo door on 
flight 
the plane crashed during a turn as it was preparing to land 
</TEXT>
