<TEXT>
federal health officials monday called 
experiments involving animals the linchpin of medical advances and 
said animal rights activists threaten to derail this progress 
animal studies have been and continue to be an 
indispensable part of the great biomedical revolution that has 
brought freedom from disease and suffering to millions of human 
beings said constance horner under secretary of health and 
human services 
virtually every major medical advance of the last hundred 
years has involved such studies the development of vaccines for 
polio tetanus diphtheria and whooping cough insulin for 
diabetics radiation and chemotherapy for cancer patients organ 
transplants and antibiotics 
in a pep talk to scientists at the national institutes of health 
in bethesda md the day before a planned animalrights rally 
there horner condemned the activities of extremists who are 
cultivating a climate of fear throughout the scientific 
research community 
scientists are being intimidated and threatened and their 
experiments sabotaged she said 
we must not permit the activities of a handful of extremists 
to deprive millions of lifesustaining and lifeenhancing fruits of 
biomedical research she said in prepared remarks 
horner said scientists including those at nih have long 
discouraged and condemned animal research that is unnecessary or 
cruel 
dr frederick goodwin head of the alcohol drug abuse and 
mental health administration told reporters earlier that both nih 
and his agency conduct research under the regulations of the animal 
welfare act of 1966 
in many cases its easier to do research with humans than 
with animals he said 
animal rights activists planned a demonstration at nih on 
tuesday to protest the use of animals in addiction research 
friends of animals which is sponsoring the protest says too 
much is being spent on animal experimentation at the expense of 
treatment and prevention of drug addiction 
the group contends scientists search for a cure for addiction 
is fruitless and fails to address the underlying social and 
psychological causes of addiction 
goodwin said the federal government is spending about 1 million 
this year and hopes to increase that to 20 million next year on 
various efforts to educate the public especially the young about 
the life sciences 
he said that was necessary in part to counter the efforts of 
animal rights activists who he said use americans lack of science 
knowledge to confuse the public 
people for the ethical treatment of animals characterized the 
effort as indoctrinating children with the idea that animals are 
no more than test tubes with whiskers 
