emerging democracies 
over the last few months we have been watching the iron 
curtain rise only to reveal a ruined landscape blanketed in 
devastating toxic industrial pollution said rep thomas luken 
democratic chairman of the house energy and commerce subcommittee 
on transportation and hazardous materials 
but he said a turf war between the environmental protection 
agency and the agency for international development threatens the 
us environmental programs in eastern europe 
movement is afoot to hand over these us environmental 
programs to the agency for international development even though 
all the expertise is at epa luken said 
timothy atkeson who is in charge of international activities at 
epa said environmental experts will be working with eastern 
europeans though they may be private contractors hired through aid 
the president has asked for flexibility atkeson said at a 
hearing of lukens subcommittee 
some programs would be best addressed by the epa some by the 
department of energy and some the private sector through aid 
contracts atkeson said 
he said epa would be the lead agency 
but luken admonished 
in the rush to provide ecomomic assistance to these ruined 
nations it is imperative that we not commit the very mistakes that 
their own governments have made since the second world war by 
choosing development at the expense of the environment 
</TEXT>
