<DOCNO> AP900423-0147 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
turboprop passenger planes will have to have a 
groundproximity warning system under federal regulations announced 
monday 
the federal aviation administration said the rule which would 
become final after a period for public comment follows a study of 
accidents in which pilots have flown aircraft into the ground with 
no apparent awareness that they were about to crash 
of 41 such accidents from 1970 to 1988 twothirds could have 
been prevented with such a system the faa said the study was 
conducted by the transportation department on a recommendation from 
the national transportation safety board which investigates 
accidents 
a groundproximity warning system sounds an alarm when a plane 
that is not preparing to land goes below a set altitude if the 
aircraft has its flaps and wheels down for landing the alarm does 
not sound 
the faa said 695 turboprop aircraft would have to add the 
system which has been required on large jetliners since 1974 and 
on smaller jets since 1978 warning devices were not previously 
required for turboprops the faa said because it was believed at 
the time that they had a greater ability to respond quickly in 
situations where altitude control was inadvertently neglected 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

