<TEXT>
former hostage robert polhill is 
alert but tired and malnourished after 1182 days in captivity in 
lebanon doctors said after examining the american educator monday 
in west germany 
polhill 55 released sunday in beirut was hungry when he 
arrived at the hospital early monday he savored some scrambled 
eggs and bacon and later enjoyed an afternoon nap of his first day 
of freedom 
proiranian shiite moslem extremists had held him since jan 24 
1987 he was the first us hostage to be released in lebanon in 
nearly 3 years 
president bush thanked iran and syria for their help in securing 
polhills release 
iranian foreign minister ali akbar velayati called for a swift 
reciprocal move freedom for a shiite cleric kidnapped by israeli 
troops in july 
velayati also said a second us hostage may be released in the 
near future 
but the bush administration repeated it would not bargain for 
freedom 
while president bush searched for opportunities for further 
releases of american hostages with phone calls to president hafez 
alassad of syria and king hussein of jordan us officials said 
no rewards diplomatic or otherwise would be made for granting 
freedom to one american while seven remain captive 
our hostages should be released unconditionally safely and 
immediately and this barbaric practice should end secretary of 
state james a baker iii said 
velayati said in an interview with cable news network 
according to the latest information that we have received from 
lebanon maybe after a few days another hostage will be released 
he did not specify the hostages nationality 
hussein musawi a leading proiranian shiite cleric also said 
one of the 17 remaining western hostages may be freed soon musawi 
is thought to have influence over islamic jihad for the liberation 
of palestine the group that held polhill 
polhill of new york an assistant professor of business studies 
at beirut university college was kidnapped from the campus on jan 
24 1987 by gunmen posing as policemen alann steen 51 of 
boston a communications instructor and jesse turner 42 of 
boise idaho a professor of mathematics and computer science were 
kidnapped with him and remain hostages 
in tehran irans state radio also said polhills release may be 
a prelude to the release of other hostages it said washington and 
other western governments must show goodwill 
us officials said they had no information of another pending 
release 
polhill first went to syria where his lebanese wife feryal 
met him they then were flown in a us c141 military transport 
plane to west germany 
welcome home pray for the others read a banner that 
greeted polhill in wiesbaden a traditional stop for newly freed 
us hostages before going home 
military spokesman cmdr john woodhouse said polhills stay at 
the us air force hospital could last a couple of days to a few 
weeks polhill would decide 
us officials told reporters polhill spoke on the phone to bush 
and baker 
were not aware of any message for bush one official said 
when the kidnappers announced an imminent release last week 
they said the freed captive would carry a message for bush 
a statement released after polhill spent two hours in the 
hospital said he is alert stable ambulatory and somewhat 
tired although he appears to be in relatively good shape he is 
malnourished and mildly dehydrated 
the statement said doctors also would evaluate polhills 
diabetes a condition he has had for 25 years 
the freed hostage is staying in vip quarters in a suite with 
hotellike accommodations 
polhill walked unaided into the hospital two airmen had 
steadied him as he got off the plane and boarded a helicopter he 
clutched a gift football under his arm as he walked slowly down the 
planes stairs greeted by cheers and applause from about 100 
people 
he wore an air force squadron cap and a poncho to protect him 
from a steady rain 
polhills two sons stephen 26 and brian 23 were expected to 
arrive tuesday from the united states 
the us officials said polhill was kept in the same building as 
turner and steen but he probably doesnt know about terry 
anderson or terry waite 
anderson chief middle east correspondent for the associated 
press is the longest held western hostage he was kidnapped march 
16 1985 most of the others have been missing at least three years 
waite 50 british envoy of the anglican church disappeared in 
lebanon on jan 20 1987 while trying to negotiate the release of 
western hostages 
the last us hostage to be freed was david jacobsen former 
director of the american university hospital in beirut he was 
kidnapped may 28 1985 and released nov 2 1986 he was held by 
another shiite faction islamic jihad or holy war 
velayati said in new york that iran and the shiite movements in 
lebanon wanted a prompt reciprocal gesture the release of sheik 
abdul karim obeid a lebanese shiite clergyman abducted by israeli 
soldiers in july 
on monday israel welcomed polhills release but made no mention 
of releasing obeid 
bush said i want all of those hostages out were not going 
to trade 
he thanked iran and syria for efforts leading to polhills 
freedom 
white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said the united 
states made no concessions to polhills abductors 
on monday the tehran times a paper close to iranian president 
hashemi rafsanjani called for release of another us hostage 
musawi told the communistrun voice of the people radio in 
lebanon the possibility of another release is in the cards but 
i dont know when how or for what 
the cleric heads islamic amal a faction within hezbollah or 
party of god believed to be an umbrella for groups holding most of 
the remaining western hostages the last westerns abducted in a 
group that includes britons an italian and west germans were two 
swiss red cross workers taken oct 16 
libyan leader moammar gadhafi called sunday for releasing all 
hostages in an appeal to moslems around the world the official 
libyan news agency jana said in a dispatch 
polhill told a syrian tv interviewer he played cards with other 
hostages during his captivity and tried to keep his mind off the 
possibility of freedom 
before leaving for west germany polhill said his joy was 
tempered by the knowledge that seven americans were still held 
he said he was angry at what was being done to me being taken 
away from my wife and family and that during his long 
confinement he strived to continue being angry knowing at all 
times that if i began to lose that anger id just sort of become a 
vegetable 
the governmentrun syrian arab news agency reported from 
damascus that bush baker and senate minority leader robert dole 
rkansas telephoned to thank syrian leaders for their help in 
gaining polhills freedom 
president bush said nothing would have been accomplished 
without syria it added 
