rights violation because he would likely be tortured by 
chinese authorities both for participation in the democracy 
movement and for his hijacking of a chinese airliner last 
december asia watch said in a message to kaifu 
asia watch appealed to kaifu on the basis of a tokyo report that 
zhang could be deported to china this week justice minister shin 
hasegawa issued an order for his extradition monday 
we obviously do not condone hijacking but no one should be 
subjected to torture said the signer of the appeal asia watch 
executive director sidney jones 
asia watch is affiliated with helsinki watch which oversees 
human rights guidelines of the 1975 helsinki agreement on eastwest 
cooperation and security 
asia watch has documented several cases of torture in chinese 
prisons including many participants in the crushed 1989 democracy 
movement ms jones said 
the tokyo high court last week upheld the japanese governments 
intention to deny political asylum to zhang overruling his defense 
that his offense was political 
