the supreme court on april 17 refused to order 
the government to reveal the names and addresses of retired or 
disabled federal workers 
the court without comment rejected an appeal by an 
organization seeking to use the information to recruit new members 
in its campaign for increased benefits for retirees 
the national association of retired federal employees used to 
have an agreement with the federal office of personnel management 
that helped the associations drive for new members 
the agency from 1979 to 1981 permitted the association to send 
information packets to newly retired federal workers through an 
independent mailing service 
after the office of personnel management ended the arrangement 
the association sought to obtain the names and addresses under the 
freedom of information act 
a federal judge ruled in favor of the association but the us 
circuit court of appeals here overturned that ruling last july 
the appeals court said revealing the names and addresses of 
retired and disabled workers would violate their privacy 
