<TEXT>
the industrialized east is not known as a haven 
for wildlife and big game but pennsylvania is taking pains to 
preserve a herd of elk as a natural legacy and a tourist 
attraction its one of only two such herds east of the mississippi 
river 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the thumping of the hovering helicopter 
shatters the tranquillity of the rugged landscape in northcentral 
pennsylvania sending a herd of female elk and their offspring 
scrambling along a hillside 
about 50 yards away a bull elk suddenly appears 1000 pounds 
of muscle and nearly 4 feet of sweeping antlers 
hes coming to protect them the pilot says over the headset 
as the chopper hovers briefly above the treetops 
indeed the dominant bulls presence appears to calm the other 
elk as the helicopter slowly circles the ridge on a sunny afternoon 
similar scenes are played out whenever crews from the 
pennsylvania game commission and the bureau of forestry conduct the 
annual census of pennsylvanias small but stable elk herd 
at last count the news was good there are 154 elk here the 
most since the count was started in the early 1970s through most 
of the last decade the herd ranged between 120 and 140 animals 
in colonial times elk roamed across much of the state but 
development an expanding population and commercial hunting made 
the native elk extinct in the state by 1867 
the roots of the current herd can be traced to 1913 when the 
game commission placed some rocky mountain elk in northcentral 
pennsylvania and in the pocono mountains region of the northeast 
the pocono herd died out leaving the only elk in the state 
confined to about a 200squaremile area in elk and cameron 
counties 
there are major concentrations of elk in the western united 
states where hunting them is popular but pennsylvania has one of 
only two herds east of the mississippi the largest concentration 
of elk in the east is in michigan 
bill drake of the game commission who supervised the census 
from a hangar at saint marys airport says for pennsylvanians 
elk are pretty impressive theyre not only large but theyre 
graceful and theyre beautiful 
the small size of the states elk range allows the searchers to 
concentrate their efforts but without snow getting an accurate 
count is impossible even though an elk is five or more times 
larger than the more common whitetailed dee the elk stand out 
against a backdrop of snow and their tracks and beds are easier to 
spot but the rest of the year their coats of brown and tan blend 
with the forest floor 
last year unseasonably warm weather prompted cancellation of 
the census this year some snow aided visibility at the start of 
the week but it was melting quickly so the crews had to step up 
the pace 
drake plotted the progress on a big wall map keeping in touch 
with the crews by radio and telephone its not easy there was an 
unconfirmed report that three large male elk were parading in a 
field several miles away they need to be confirmed by game wardens 
before they can be added to the count 
is there anything we can do to find those three drake asks 
we can use every elk we can find 
he predicted 171 but was resigned to the fact that the actual 
count would fall far short 
it is frustrating for instance one ground crew reported 
finding three fresh beds but saw only two bull elk they debated 
for a few minutes before drake quietly but firmly said he wouldnt 
count an elk that nobody saw 
the census also counts the number of elk that have died in an 
average year 13 animals die in 1989 the mortality count was 10 
five including one found with its antlers removed with a chain 
saw were killed illegally two were klled by farmers because their 
crops were being destroyed one died of unknown causes and one a 
goliathlike victim of a much smaller foe died of malnutrition 
with porcupine quills in its mouth 
hunters are not allowed to kill elk in pennsylvania but drake 
and others acknowledge a limited hunt is not out of the question at 
some point in the future they are quiet about it in the early 
1980s when the commission publicly said a hunt might be held 
farmers and poachers jumped the gun twentysix elk were killed 
illegally in one year 
they thought if we had trouble with too many elk theyd 
handle it locally rather than let people come in and hunt from 
outside the county drake said thats what we think happened 
a local elk committee has been set up to keep farmers sportsmen 
and the game commission informed of illegal kills to draw elk away 
from farmland some public land has been clearcut to provide food 
for the herd 
the herd has become a tourist attraction in recent years and 
mark rupprecht owner of elk county ammo and arms knows where they 
gather 
in the fall for instance motorists can see as many as 60 elk 
in a field just outside town theres a lot of traffic out 
there rupprecht said its hard to get a parking space 
drake adds if we can maintain elk its kind of an indication 
that we still have some areas in pennsylvania that have a pristine 
quality of environment 
