<DOCNO> AP900423-0233 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
chinas listless economy wont begin to recover 
until the second half of the year jeopardizing the nations 
industrial growth target a government economist said monday 
zhang zhongji of the state statistical bureau told a news 
conference that the economy had failed to respond to several 
measures taken during the first quarter of the year 
he said an infusion of 42 billion in loans for slumping 
industries double the amount for the same period of 1989 had 
contributed mainly to further overstocking of unsold products 
zhang provided figures most already released showing zero 
growth in industrial output value over the first quarter with a 
31 percent downturn in retail sales and sharp declines in the 
production of durable consumer goods 
he said austerity measures initiated in late 1988 to slow down 
inflation and runaway economic growth had shown some positive 
results retail prices were up only 39 percent from the previous 
year the lowest increase since 1988 energy production was up a 
solid 67 percent the trade balance was favorable and goods on the 
marketplace were plentiful 
but there has been no fundamental change in the slump of the 
market stagnation in industrial production and poor economic 
efficiency he said 
zhang predicted little economic growth in the second quarter he 
said the economy will only begin to recover in the second half of 
the year 
reaching the government target of industrial growth of 5 percent 
to 6 percent will be a very difficult and arduous task he said 
zhang said the economic slump caused concern for many people 
but declined to characterize the situation as a recession he said 
it was not surprising to see some stagnation and even decline 
as the government tries to control inflation and adjust the 
industrial structure 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

