<TEXT>
the supreme court today refused to block an 
alaska state court trial of a lawsuit that accuses oil companies of 
underpaying the state for oil leases 
the justices without comment rejected arguments the oil 
companies cannot get a fair trial in alaska because all residents 
including judges and prospective jurors would share in any 
additional money the firms could be ordered to pay 
alaska officials sued in 1983 seeking damages from 19 oil 
producers who received state leases to mine the states north slope 
the state said the companies underestimated the value of oil and 
gas taken from prudhoe bay and kuparuk river fields 
three companies that are trying to kill the suit said 26 
billion could be at stake and that could translate into 70 a year 
indefinitely for each state resident qualified to share in the 
proceeds the three companies are standard alaska production co 
exxon corp and chevron usa 
a share of all oil royalties go into a special state fund 
created so that alaska residents can share in the states mineral 
wealth 
about half the yearly income produced by the fund is distributed 
to qualified residents in the form of dividends 
the oil companies said the existence of the fund means it is 
impossible to get an impartial judge and jury in alaska to consider 
the states suit for additional payments 
every judge and juror in alaska has an inherent bias 
lawyers for the oil companies said since a successful suit by the 
state could put more money in their pockets 
the 9th us circuit court of appeals ruled last year the 
companies bid to use the federal courts to block the state court 
proceedings is premature 
the appeals court said even assuming that each state resident 
stands to gain 70 a year from the suit we do not have 
sufficient facts before us to determine whether such a sum is a 
substantial financial interest compelling disqualification of 
judges and jurors 
it is also possible that some judges and prospective jurors 
would be willing to forgo any extra benefits from the suit the 
appeals court said 
the case is bp exploration vs baily 891375 
</TEXT>
