<DOCNO> AP900423-0249 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
history is repeating itself in cyprus 
the east mediterranean island which grew fabulously rich in the 
middle ages as the main link between europe and the orient is 
becoming an international offshore banking and business center 
the merchants of cyprus in the 15th century grew so wealthy that 
they used to produce fruit bowls laden with diamonds and other gems 
for important visitors who could choose one as a gift 
cypriot hospitality is not so lavish now but official 
statistics list more than 6000 offshore companies including 19 
foreign banks and numerous financial services based on the 
island which has emerged as the principal transit point to what 
used to be the thriving city of beirut lebanon 
many companies are there in name only as cyrprus provides a 
convenient mailing address and a way to keep a presence in a part 
of the world continuallly racked by war and terrorism 
but nearly 700 maintain offices employing more than 3000 
people the central bank said they pumped 95 million into the 
economy of the greek sector of the wardivided island last year 
cyprus was divided in 1974 when the turkish army invaded and 
seized the northern onethird of the island it is now a breakway 
turkish cypriot republic 
the island has become the regional center for major news 
organizations including the wests three major wire services it 
also has the worlds fastest growing shipping registry 
nearly 2000 ships call cyprus home making it numerically the 
third largest fleet in the world in terms of tonnage it ranks 
seventh with a gross total of nearly 19 million tons 
the island has a long way to go to catch up with bahrain 
financial center of the oilrich persian gulf with 60 offshore 
banks 
but recently banks from the soviet union yugoslavia and jordan 
have set up in cyprus and a group of 30 japanese bankers visited 
the island 
cyprus got its start as a regional business hub when the civil 
war in lebanon 100 miles to the southeast broke out in april 1975 
many beirutbased companies relocated to cyprus a bonanza for 
the island that the year before had been ravaged by the turkish 
invasion 
the majority greek cypriots who lost rich farmlands tourist 
facilities and a major port in the invasion had little choice but 
to rebuild their economy with new tourist facilities and offshore 
business 
tourism lifeblood of the economy has now reached 13 million 
visitors a year bringing in an estimated 900 million annually for 
the 550000 greek cypriots 
it still is expanding hani yamani son of the former saudi oil 
minister ahmet zaki yamani recently announced a 300 million 
project for the most luxurious hotel in the world a greek 
history theme park and other facilities on 2500 acres on cyprus 
west coast 
but the focus is to build cyprus up as a business center it got 
a major boost when george vassiliou a selfmade millionaire 
business consultant was elected president in february 1988 
addressing a business seminar last month vassiliou said that in 
a small country with scant natural resources the provision of 
services is probably the only sector of activity that we can 
develop steadily to provide employment and a steady increase in the 
standard of living of our people 
late last year the central bank launched a campaign to attract 
more investment and offshore business 
central bank gov afxentis afxentiou stressed the islands 
geographical position at the crossroads of europe asia and africa 
and its satellite communications network as advantages for 
businessmen 
he also cited air and sea transport banking and legal services 
a skilled labor force a low cost of living with minimal inflation 
and generous financial incentives half the normal income tax rate 
and onetenth of the normal corporation tax 
other advantages are a high living standard in a society with 
such a low crime rate that automobiles can be left unlocked in the 
street also most people speak english a legacy of british 
colonial rule that ended with independence in 1960 
</TEXT>
