<TEXT>
the supreme court on monday agreed to review a 
ruling that if upheld could cost a bank holding company over 13 
million in damages 
the court said it will decide whether first american bankshares 
inc fabi violated federal securities law prior to a 1987 merger 
of its subsidiary virginia bankshares inc and the first american 
bank of virginia 
the 4th us circuit court of appeals ruled last dec 15 that 
fabi violated securities law by sending first american bank of 
virginia minority shareholders misleading proxy statements 
before the merger virginia bankshares owned 85 percent of the 
stock in the first american bank of virginia a merger was proposed 
so fabi through its subsidiary would buy up the remaining 15 
percent and own all the banks stock 
fabi paid 42 per share for the minority shareholders stock 
but the merger was challenged in federal court by doris i 
sandberg who owned 2242 shares of first american bank of virginia 
a federal jury ruled for her and awarded her 43956 or 18 
per share in damages 
the presiding judge had refused to certify the suit as a class 
action filed in behalf of all the banks minority shareholders 
the 4th circuit court upheld the jurys verdict but ruled that 
the trial judge should have certified the lawsuit as a class action 
the result of this ruling is that the 43956 judgment that 
the jury awarded to sandberg might now be transformed on remand 
into a judgment in excess of 13 million lawyers for fabi told 
the justices 
in the appeal acted on monday the fabi lawyers argued among 
other things that the proxy statements found to have been 
misleading could not possibly have affected the outcome of the 
proxy vote the appeal said that fabi had far more than the 
twothirds of the share votes needed to bring about the merger 
without the consent of any minority shareholders 
the appeal also contended that no minority shareholder proved to 
have actually relied on the statements 
the appeals court ruled that reliance does not have to be proved 
in lawsuits invoking the securities law banning false or misleading 
proxy statements 
the case is virginia bankshares inc vs sandberg 891448 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

