<TEXT>
the right to strike a 
constitutional guarantee unions consider sacred would be severely 
restricted by legislation president carlos menem sent to congress 
on monday 
the peronist party president elected last may with the support 
of organized labor said the measure is needed to curtail walkouts 
that have disrupted schools commuter trains federal courts 
municipal hospitals phones and other public services 
if we obtain consensus for it thats great if we dont we 
will push it through anyway a determined menem said last week 
the measure would require unions that provide essential 
services to give at least 10 days notice of a strike and submit 
to mediation by the labor ministry that could last 15 more days 
management would be authorized to hire enough workers for a 
minimum level of service if strikers did not comply with the 
notice or tried to block all service they could be fired and 
unions could lose their legal status 
the legislation cites public health transport energy schools 
and telecommunications as essential services and leaves open 
the possibility that strikes by private unions also might be 
regulated 
victor de gennaro director of the 145000member association of 
state employees said the bill has as its objective the 
intimidation of workers 
juan manuel casella the civic radical unions candidate for 
vice president in the may 1989 national elections said the 
legislation is aimed more to punish workers than to regulate 
strikes 
the measure which menem at first said he would impose by 
decree upset even peronist legislators reluctant to alienate a 
group whose support has been steadfast during three decades of 
repression 
peronist sen orando britos said flatly he would vote against 
it a bloc of eight dissident peronist deputies in the lower house 
indicated they would too 
technically the ruling party has an absolute majority in the 
senate and a working majority in the chamber of deputies 
menem 59 is a lifelong member of the party and a threetime 
provincial governor he was arrested and held in detention with 
many peronist politicians and labor leaders following the march 
1976 military coup that toppled president isabel peron 
the measure is not his first that unions say is antilabor 
since menem took office last july amid hyperinflation and 
recession public service rates have risen faster than salaries 
contributing to the contraction of real wages 
despite campaign promises of massive wage hikes and a 
productive revolution menem has imposed an austerity budget 
that has exacerbated unemployment 
as many as 48 million argentines of a workforce of 125 
million are unemployed or underemployed according to the labor 
ministry 
menem appointed executives from argentinas largest 
multinational company as his first two economy ministers he 
ignored union pleas by lifting controls on wages prices and 
foreign exchange and by committing the government to sell 
moneylosing public companies 
anticipating conflict menem tried to unseat saul ubaldini as 
leader of the 3millionmember general labor confederation that 
failed but the confederation split into rival camps 
in recent weeks public school teachers from grade school 
through university have boycotted classes employees of the 
stateowned airline and telephone company have staged wildcat 
strikes doctors at municipal hospitals and court clerks have 
walked off the job 
unions are demanding pay increases which the government says it 
cannot afford also they are seeking a greater voice in the sale 
of state companies two of which the airline and telephone 
company are to be sold this year 
after months of currency devaluation and inflation that soared 
by 95 percent last month there are signs the government is 
bringing the economy under control 
inflation in april is projected at 12 percent to 15 percent the 
austral has held steady at 5000 for every us dollar or less 
since early march prices in supermarkets and department stores 
have begun to come down 
after an estimated 60000 union members staged an 
antigovernment demonstration on the steps of congress that many 
and more rallied at government house to shout their support for 
menem 
</TEXT>
