<TEXT>
sir james goldsmiths hoylake investments ltd 
said today it would not renew its 22 billion bid for the british 
conglomerate bat industries plc 
the hostile bid of 878 pence or 1431 a share would have been 
the worlds secondlargest takeover after kohlberg kravis roberts 
amp cos 25 billion purchase of rjr nabisco inc completed early 
last year 
the hoylake investors group dropped the bid because it simply 
felt that the combination of the time the bid would take to get 
through us regulatory hurdles and the costs thereof tipped the 
riskreward ratio the wrong way said a spokesman for one of 
hoylakes merchant banks who spoke anonymously 
hoylake said in a statement the directors of hoylake wish bat 
and its unbundled offspring great success within their new 
structures 
hoylakes withdrawal comes after californias state insurance 
regulators decided april 9 to bar a change of control of bats 
farmers insurance group inc of los angeles the offer needed 
approval from the commissioners of the nine states where farmers 
operates 
the withdrawal is a major defeat for goldsmith an anglofrench 
financier who has built a worldwide reputation by taking over and 
breaking up companies 
the news of the withdrawal came after londons stock exchange 
closed bat shares ended at 724 pence or 1180 a share down 4 
pence 
hoylake launched the offer last july but suspended it in 
september while it sought the clearance from the us state 
insurance commissioners 
bat has been restructuring itself to fend off the bid the 
hoylake withdrawal probably will not affect the restructuring 
which is designed to boost bats share price 
i am pleased that hoylke and axamidi have finally abandoned 
their bid bat chairman patrick sheehy said in a statement issued 
in the united states we can now devote our full attention to 
running the continuing group based on our financial services and 
tobacco businesses 
the hoylake investors group also included british merchant 
banker jacob rothschild and australian businessman kerry packer 
goldsmith and other shareholders have complained that bats 
stock price does not reflect the stocks real value because it is 
dragged down by the slower growth of its tobacco businesses 
bat is selling and spinning off its retailing and paper 
businesses to concentrate on tobacco and financial services 
last week bat announced the sale of its us retailer marshall 
