about 850 workers for the santa fe railroad face 
layoffs because of sharp drops in shipments of automobiles and 
grain two of the railroads most important commodities the 
company announced monday 
some of the layoffs will start as early as a week from 
today robert gehrt spokesman for the atchison topeka and santa 
fe railway co said monday we hope to have most of them in 
place by may 15 
the layoffs will affect about 125 workers at the locomotive shop 
at san bernardino calif and an additional 100 from the railroad 
car repair shops in topeka kan the company said in a statement 
about 70 workers will be laid off from the companys centralized 
work equipment plant at albuquerque nm and 15 will be laid off 
at the newton kan rail plant the statement said 
an additional 200 section gang workers one from each gang and 
75 specialty gang employees will be laid off 
about 100 management employees will be laid off but the 
departments affected by those cutbacks have not been determined 
company president michael r haverty said in the statement 
santa fe which employs about 18000 people said the remainder 
of the layoffs are not expected to have a major impact in any one 
community 
automobile shipping dropped 47 percent in early april and grain 
shipping declined 40 percent the two normally account for about 22 
percent of the railroads business 
when you get a big hit like this in those two areas its 
something to be concerned about gehrt said 
piggybacking semitrailers account for more than 20 percent of 
the companys business gehrt said while shipments of food and 
farm products other than grain accounts for about 14 percent and 
chemicals for about 12 percent 
haverty said the layoffs are similar to seasonal employment 
reductions the company has undergone in the past but are more 
severe 
santa fe blamed a 10 million increase in fuel costs during the 
first quarter and mediocre firstquarter performance for the 
layoffs 
the company reported firstquarter operating income of 661 
million compared with 342 million for the same quarter last year 
but we had a big property tax refund in california of over 30 
million this quarter and without that we would have been just 
about even gehrt said and last years figures included a 
special charge of over 50 million the first quarter of 1990 
wasnt a good quarter 
