<TEXT>
bond prices slipped monday in light trading 
echoing declines overseas as the market awaited economic reports 
due later this week 
the treasurys benchmark 30year bond fell 732 point or about 
219 per 1000 face amount its yield which rises when prices 
fall rose to 896 percent from 894 percent late friday 
the last time the yield on the 30year bond was as high was last 
may 11 when it stood at 907 percent 
the 30year bond has plunged more than 41 per 1000 over the 
past seven trading days in response to signs of increasing 
inflation a stronger economy and worries about upcoming bond 
issues including the treasurys quarterly refunding auction set 
for next month 
higher inflation and an economic upturn could prompt the federal 
reserve to keep interest rates high higher rates decrease the 
value of fixedreturn investments such as bonds 
an increased supply of bonds can temporarily drive down prices 
until the market absorbs the new issues 
there were few forces acting on the bond market monday except 
for a softness in prices in overseas trading before us trading 
began said william v sullivan director of money market research 
for dean witter reynolds inc 
it was lethargic he said so the market was just really 
drifting the markets looking ahead to the upcoming data release 
on tuesday the government is scheduled to release reports on 
durable goods orders for march and the employmentcost index for 
the first quarter while the first report on the gross national 
product for 1990 is set to be announced friday 
the market had little reaction to news that west germany agreed 
to exchange a limited number of east german marks for west german 
marks at a 11 ratio some economists believe such a ratio could 
cause inflation in west germany but sullivan said bond traders 
probably viewed the proposal as preliminary 
in the secondary market for treasury bonds prices of shortterm 
governments fell from 132 point to lsqb point intermediate 
maturities lost between 532 point and 732 point and longterm 
issues were off from 316 point to point according to telerate 
inc a financial information service 
the movement of a point is equivalent to a change of 10 in the 
price of a bond with a 1000 face value 
the shearson lehman hutton daily treasury bond index which 
measures price movements on all outstanding treasury issues with 
maturities of a year or longer fell 141 to 113305 
in the taxexempt market the bond buyer index of 40 actively 
traded municipal bonds fell 532 point to 90 1532 point the 
average yield to maturity rose to 761 percent from 759 percent 
late thursday 
at an auction monday the treasury sold 82 billion in 
threemonth bills at an average discount rate of 778 percent up 
from 771 percent last week another 82 billion was sold in 
sixmonth bills at an average discount rate of 791 percent up 
from 775 percent last week 
the rates were the highest since threemonth bills sold for 780 
percent april 9 and sixmonth bills averaged 792 percent march 19 
in the secondary market for treasury bills yields on 
threemonth bills rose to 797 percent as the discount rose 3 basis 
points to 772 percent yields on sixmonth bills rose to 828 
percent as the discount gained 6 basis points to 786 percent 
yields on oneyear bills rose to 849 percent as the discount 
gained 6 basis point to 789 percent 
a basis point is onehundredth of a percentage point the yield 
is the annualized return on an investment in a treasury bill the 
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face 
value which is paid at maturity 
the federal funds rate the interest rate banks charge each 
other on overnight loans was quoted at 8 316 percent unchanged 
from late friday 
