american and west european officials agreed on 
monday to strengthen their economic and political ties but 
disagreed on how to resolve a simmering discord over farm subsidies 
secretary of state james a baker iii who led the us 
delegation to the talks with the european economic community said 
the two sides discussed the changes in eastern europe and how these 
would affect the eec and the united states 
the two teams also discussed the soviet sanctions against 
lithuania baker said the eec shared with the united states the 
growing international concerns about the soviet response to the 
secessionist baltic state 
the useec ministerial talks held for the first time in the 
united states since they began in 1981 also focused on the effects 
of german unification on the european economy the subject as well 
as the us views will come up saturday at the eec summit in 
dublin ireland 
both baker and eec president jacques delors stressed the 
importance of coordinating their positions as the pace of european 
unification accelerates toward the target date of 1992 and as the 
eec tries to handle the changes brought about by the collapse of 
communism in eastern europe 
the united states is particularly concerned that as the eec 
moves toward a monetary and trade union among its 12 member 
nations us business will be shut out the eec is determined to 
reassure the americans that the new system will leave plenty of 
room for trade with the united states 
this meeting has taken place at a crossroads in atlantic 
history at a time of new significance to the partnership between 
the community and the united states delors told reporters after 
his daylong talks with baker 
both sides agreed on the need to bring the uruguay round of 
international trade talks to a successful conclusion by the end of 
the year 
but officials on both sides said they were worried that their 
dispute on agriculture could endanger the trade talks among 96 
nations which began in 1986 and are intended to liberalize 
commerce around the world 
the agriculture dispute revolves around the question of farm 
subsidies with the united states demanding the 12 eec nations do 
away with support for farmers and the europeans saying this is an 
unrealistic demand 
its certain the united states wants to go down the road f 
reform more than the eec said agriculture secretary clayton 
yeutter that doesnt mean we cant resolve our differences until 
december 
the two delegations agreed to speed up their talks on the 
subject and appointed staff members to deal with various aspects of 
the dispute including the question of market access and export 
subsidies 
but the eecs agriculture commissioner raymond mcsharr 
cautioned that there are many difficulties and they musnt be 
underestimated 
